  "text": "∘ , but the 420 s exposures were taken for the rest of position angles. The spectral dispersions were 2.2 and 0.66Å/pix, respectively, for spectral bands of blue part, (3750Å) − (5500Å), and red part, (6450Å) − (7100Å). The resolution, as measured on the night sky lines, was ∼7.5Å (FWHM) for the blue part, and ∼1.8Å (FWHM) for 4 Advances in Astronomy the red part. As it is seen, the nuclear components in both of these samples show quite similar emission lines in their spectra. Treating the instrumental profile and the intrinsic profile to sum as Gaussians is a good approximation [CITATION_1] . A formal solution, in general, is a deconvolution, but this comes very close to the same result. Thus, unfolding wholly the forbidden [OIII] 5007 line profile into its Gaussian component, the question can be resolved by subtraction of instrumental broadening (for the real Doppler broadening of the [OIII] 5007 lines see Table 1 ).",
